Step 1. Compute Debt to Equity Ratio.  
• Total Liabilities: We add Accounts Payable and Taxes Payable from the balance sheet.  
  Accounts Payable = 1,260,000.00  
  Taxes Payable = 341,835.08  
  Total Liabilities = 1,260,000.00 + 341,835.08 = 1,601,835.08  
• Total Owner's Equity is given as 10,964,263.48.  
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner's Equity  
  = 1,601,835.08 / 10,964,263.48 ≈ 0.1460 → approximately 0.15  

Step 2. Compute Net Profit Margin.  
• Net Profit from the income statement = -2,035,736.52  
• Total Revenue = 6,836,701.10  
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (-2,035,736.52 / 6,836,701.10) × 100 ≈ -29.78%  

Step 3. Compute Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio.  
• Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities from the cash flow statement = -6,856,840.58  
• Total Current Liabilities from the balance sheet = 1,601,835.08  
• Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Total Current Liabilities  
  = -6,856,840.58 / 1,601,835.08 ≈ -4.278 → approximately -4.28  

Thus, the solution in the requested JSON format is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.15",
    "Net Profit Margin": "-29.78%",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-4.28"
  }
}
